<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-11-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-11-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="96" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d96">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Conger</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-11-23"><hi rend="italic">November 23,
                                    1901</hi>.</date></dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 416.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            dispatch No. 779, of the 16th ultimo, inclosing a copy of correspondence
                            between you and the Chinese foreign office upon the question of the
                            continued residence in Peking of foreign merchants who located there
                            during the occupation of that place by the allied forces.</p>
                        <p>The Department approves your reply to the Chinese foreign office, as
                            given in the inclosure to the dispatch.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>